				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The VBL test ROMs treated the beginning of VBL as the earliest that $2002 would read back $80. The above tests reveal that /NMI to the CPU is actually asserted one PPU clock earlier, and that reading at that time prevents the flag from being set.<br /><br />I don't know the exact relation of VBL to a particular scanline. I pretty much have assumed that it occurs at the beginning of the 20 non-displaying scanlines of a frame. I could test this by using timed $2006 writes while PPU rendering is off.</div>
<br />So this is how I understand that. The rest scanline, after the whole screen render process, is 341 PPU cycles long. At the end of the 340th cycle (or during it) /NMI is asserted, and at the end of the 341st cycle (or during it) VBL is set. Then, VBL period runs for its 20 scanlines. Now, reading at the end of the 340th cycle (or during it) will prevent VBL flag to be set.</div>

